events.title: Birth
events.summary: C. P. E. Bach was born in Weimar to a prominent musical family, being the fifth child of Johann Sebastian Bach. His early environment was heavily influenced by music, with his father serving as a key figure in his education.
events.fun_version: C. P. E. Bach was born in Weimar to a prominent musical family, so posh that even the cat had a violin! Being the fifth child of Johann Sebastian Bach, there was no shortage of jamming sessions. His early environment was heavily influenced by music, and with a father who was a maestro, little C. P. E. probably thought music was as essential as brushing his teeth!

events.title: Education at St. Thomas School
events.summary: At the age of ten, Bach entered St. Thomas School in Leipzig, where he began to receive a formal education in music, further shaped by his father's role as cantor there.
events.fun_version: Bach at ten was not just another kid at St. Thomas School; he was the tiny maestro in training, receiving a formal education in music! His dad, the cantor there, was probably thinking, "If I'm going to be stuck with this kid, he better play something catchy!"

events.title: Appointment in Berlin
events.summary: Shortly after graduation, Bach was appointed to the service of Crown Prince Frederick of Prussia, marking the beginning of his influential years in Berlin.
events.fun_version: Right after his grand finale at the graduation ceremony, Bach landed a gig with Crown Prince Frederick of Prussia. I mean, who wouldn’t want a ruler who can also appreciate a good symphony? It was the beginning of his influential years and big-time popularity in the big, bustling Berlin!

events.title: Degree in Jurisprudence
events.summary: Bach pursued studies in jurisprudence and graduated with a degree, although he would not practice law and instead devoted himself to music.
events.fun_version: Bach pursued studies in jurisprudence and graduated with a degree, but instead of practicing law, he humorously traded his legal briefs for musical sheets. Who needs courtroom drama when you can have a symphony of strings, right?

events.title: Promoted to Chamber Musician
events.summary: In 1746, Bach was promoted to the position of chamber musician, which allowed him to collaborate with other prominent musicians of his time.
events.fun_version: In 1746, Bach finally got a promotion to chamber musician, allowing him to collaborate with other prominent musicians of his time. But let’s be honest – he was just tired of playing hide and seek with them! Who knew collaborating could be so much fun?

events.title: Success at Hamburg
events.summary: After moving to Hamburg, Bach began producing significant ecclesiastical music, including the oratorio 'Die Israeliten in der Wüste,' showcasing his growing influence.
events.fun_version: Bach didn't just move to Hamburg; he practically packed his bags and said, "I'm off to compose music so good, it might just have the angels dancing!" Between writing tunes, he’s putting the “fun” in "funeral oratorio" with his significant piece 'Die Israeliten in der Wüste,' showcasing his growing influence and the impact of his move on his ecclesiastical music.

events.title: Publication of Treatise
events.summary: Bach published a seminal treatise on keyboard techniques, establishing himself at the forefront of European music and laying the groundwork for future musicians.
events.fun_version: Bach published a seminal treatise on keyboard techniques, establishing himself as the rockstar of European music and laying the groundwork for future musicians—talk about setting the bar high!

events.title: Death
events.summary: Emanuel Bach passed away, leaving behind a rich legacy of music that had a lasting impact on future composers.
events.fun_version: Emanuel Bach shuffled off this mortal coil, leaving behind a musical treasure chest that future composers will pick through like kids in a candy store, and his melodies will ensure that he’s not forgotten anytime soon!
